sysID.name: sysID
sysID.description: An integer which serves to identify the type of SmartStack.

sysReset.name: sysReset
sysReset.description: The time, in centiseconds, before the device should reboot. A GetResponse value of zero indicates that no reboot time has been specified.

sysTrapPort.name: sysTrapPort
sysTrapPort.description: Zero, or the UDP port number to which a second copy of SNMP traps should be sent. Valid values are zero through 65535.

kxhwDiagCode.name: kxhwDiagCode
kxhwDiagCode.description: Additional diagnostics information concerning the slot's module.

kxhwManufData.name: kxhwManufData
kxhwManufData.description: A 24-byte array which contains the part number, serial number and hardware revision level of this module.

kxswNumber.name: kxswNumber
kxswNumber.description: The number of file sets. The default is 2.

kxswFilesetTable.name: kxswFilesetTable
kxswFilesetTable.description: A list of the software file sets stored. The first file set refers to the one that was used when ELS-100 last booted. The second file set refers to the one which will be used when ELS-100 reboots or reloads any hardware module.

kxswFilesetEntry.name: kxswFilesetEntry
kxswFilesetEntry.description: A set of objects for each file set.

kxswIndex.name: kxswIndex
kxswIndex.description: The file set number, beginning with 1 for the first file set. This number always matches the instance of the swFiles. For example, {swIndex 2} contains the value '2'.

kxswDesc.name: kxswDesc
kxswDesc.description: The description (0-255 bytes) of the software file set.

kxswCount.name: kxswCount
kxswCount.description: The number of files in the file set. This number may range from 1 to 255.

kxswType.name: kxswType
kxswType.description: The types of the files within the file set.

kxswSizes.name: kxswSizes
kxswSizes.description: An array (4 octets per file), containing the size of each of the files. Each size is encoded as a series of 4 bytes, which should be converted into a 32 bit integer.

kxswStarts.name: kxswStarts
kxswStarts.description: An array (4 octets per file), containing the software's execution starting address of each of the files. Each address is encoded as a series of 4 bytes, which should be converted into a 32 bit integer.

kxswBases.name: kxswBases
kxswBases.description: An array (4 octets per file), containing the software's base loading address of each of the files. Each address is encoded as a series of 4 bytes, which should be converted into a 32 bit integer.

kxswFlashBank.name: kxswFlashBank
kxswFlashBank.description: The bank number where the software file set resides.

kxadminFatalErr.name: kxadminFatalErr
kxadminFatalErr.description: This is a 32 byte array which contains information about the cause of the previous system reset. This will describe the circumstances which forced the system software to perform a reboot. The values in the first byte have the following meanings (0) Power failure, (1) Watchdog Timeout, (2) NMS Requested Shutdown, (3-255) Fatal Error (next byte contains the hwIndex of the module which encountered the error; remaining 30 bytes contain additional information).

kxadminAnyPass.name: kxadminAnyPass
kxadminAnyPass.description: The authentication password (0-24 bytes) which must match the community name in an SNMP PDU, in order for the operation to be performed. A zero length password indicates that any community name is acceptable.

kxadminGetPass.name: kxadminGetPass
kxadminGetPass.description: The authentication password (0-24 bytes) which must match the community name in an SNMP Get PDU (except for Debug or password parameters). A zero length password indicates that any community name is acceptable. Alternatively, it is acceptable if the community name matches configAnyPass.

kxadminNMSIPAddr.name: kxadminNMSIPAddr
kxadminNMSIPAddr.description: The address of the NMS to which Trap PDUs are to be sent. A value of zero indicates that Trap PDUs should be sent to the NMS last heard from.

kxadminStorageFailure.name: kxadminStorageFailure
kxadminStorageFailure.description: Whether the ELS-100's storage facility for its configuration parameters has failed (the ELS-100 may not be able to reboot after such a failure).

kxadminAuthenticationFailure.name: kxadminAuthenticationFailure
kxadminAuthenticationFailure.description: All nulls, or the IP source address within the last SNMP PDU which caused an SNMP authentication failure.

kxadminArpEntries.name: kxadminArpEntries
kxadminArpEntries.description: The number of ARP entries for all interfaces.

kxadminArpStatics.name: kxadminArpStatics
kxadminArpStatics.description: The number of statically defined ARP entries for all interfaces.

kxadminArpOverflows.name: kxadminArpOverflows
kxadminArpOverflows.description: The number of times a ARP entry could not be learned due to insufficient address table space.

kxadminRipPreference.name: kxadminRipPreference
kxadminRipPreference.description: The value to assign to ipRouteMetric2, when adding a RIP-learned entry to the IP Routing Table.

kxadminRipRouteDiscards.name: kxadminRipRouteDiscards
kxadminRipRouteDiscards.description: The number of times a route learned via RIP was not added to the IP Routing Table due to insufficient Routing Table space.

kxadminRebootConfig.name: kxadminRebootConfig
kxadminRebootConfig.description: The configuration file that will be used when the ELS-100 reboots. This parameter is normally automatically set by the ELS-100; however, an NMS may explicitly set it to either no-change (1) or revert-to-defaults (3).

kxswdisDesc.name: kxswdisDesc
kxswdisDesc.description: The description (0-32 bytes) of the software set currently being downloaded, or a description of the software set last downloaded since the ELS100-16 booted.

kxswdisAccess.name: kxswdisAccess
kxswdisAccess.description: The version of software that may be downloaded. Attempts to download other versions of software will be rejected. The value for swdisAccess is embedded within the software files that are to be distributed via TFTP. Its value may be derived from the names of the software files. The NMS operator may wish to use the following special values: protected (1) No software downloads will be accepted any-software (2) A software download of any version of new software will be accepted - this is the factory default

kxswdisWriteStatus.name: kxswdisWriteStatus
kxswdisWriteStatus.description: The status of the erase/write operation.

kxswdisConfigIp.name: kxswdisConfigIp
kxswdisConfigIp.description: The IP address of the NMS (i.e., any IP host) that is allowed to use TFTP to send/retrieve the configuration file of the ELS100-16. A value of 0.0.0.0 (which is the factory specified default) prevents any NMS from obtaining access, while a value of 255.255.255.255 gives every NMS permission.

kxswdisConfigRetryTime.name: kxswdisConfigRetryTime
kxswdisConfigRetryTime.description: The number of seconds that the ELS-100 will wait for an acknowledgment before it retransmits an unacknowledged TFTP data block. The factory specified default is 5 seconds.

kxswdisConfigTotalTimeout.name: kxswdisConfigTotalTimeout
kxswdisConfigTotalTimeout.description: The number of seconds that the ELS-100 will wait for an acknowledgment to a data block before it cancels a TFTP session. The factory specified default is 25 seconds.

kxaddrStatics.name: kxaddrStatics
kxaddrStatics.description: The number of static addresses which are currently stored in the ELS100-16.

kxaddrDynamics.name: kxaddrDynamics
kxaddrDynamics.description: The number of learned addresses in the address table.

kxaddrDynamicMax.name: kxaddrDynamicMax
kxaddrDynamicMax.description: The maximum number of spanning tree addresses which have been learned since the ELS100-16 was last booted (or this parameter was last reset by the NMS).

kxaddrDynamicOverflows.name: kxaddrDynamicOverflows
kxaddrDynamicOverflows.description: The number times an address was not learned due to insufficient address table space.

kxaddrFlags.name: kxaddrFlags
kxaddrFlags.description: Flags to describe the use and control of this address entry. Each bit has a different meaning. The NMS must always set either entry-static, entry-none, or entry-mesh; however, for GetRequests, the NMS will see either no bits set (if the entry does not exist), or exactly one of the following bits set: entry-dynamic-local = 30, entry-dynamic-remote = 29, entry-static = 28, entry-other = 27, entry-none = 26, entry-mesh = 25, entry-statistics = 24, Bit 31 is reserved. Any combination of the restriction bits (bits 23-21) may be set for any type of entry, except entry-other or entry-mesh: entry-no-source = 23, entry-no-multi = 22, Bit 21 is reserved, Bits 20-18 are reserved. Exactly one of the special entry bits (bits 17-10) must be set for entry-other entries, and none of the bits may be set for other than entry-other entries: entry-all-lmas = 17, entry-any-lma = 16, entry-lma = 15, entry-port = 14, entry-bpdu = 13, entry-reserved = 12, Bits 11-10 are reserved for future expansion. Bits 9-0 are reserved.

kxaddrMAC.name: kxaddrMAC
kxaddrMAC.description: The MAC address for this address definition.

kxaddrPort.name: kxaddrPort
kxaddrPort.description: The port through which this address is connected to the ELS100 (only valid for entry-dynamic-local, entry-statistics, and entry-port entries).

kxaddrOperation.name: kxaddrOperation
kxaddrOperation.description: The operation to be performed upon the described address. The possibilities include: read-random (1), read-next (2), update (4), delete (5), read-block (6).

kxaddrIndex.name: kxaddrIndex
kxaddrIndex.description: The index number to be used for read-next and read-block operations. When the ELS-100 boots, addrIndex is initialized to -1.

kxaddrNext.name: kxaddrNext
kxaddrNext.description: The next value to use for addrIndex, when you use read-next or read-block operations to read the address table. When the ELS-100 boots, addrNext is initialized to -1.

kxaddrBlockSize.name: kxaddrBlockSize
kxaddrBlockSize.description: The number of addresses contained by addrBlock. This parameter is only used for dumping blocks of MAC addresses.

kxaddrBlock.name: kxaddrBlock
kxaddrBlock.description: A series of 0-700 octets, which represents 0-100 addresses. Each address consists of a 6 octet MAC address followed by a 1 byte port number. If the port number is zero, then the address is that of a specially configured address; otherwise, the address is a dynamically learned address. This parameter is only used for dumping blocks of MAC addresses

kxifTable.name: kxifTable
kxifTable.description: A list of interface entries; one per port.

kxifEntry.name: kxifEntry
kxifEntry.description: A set of objects for an interface entry.

kxifIndex.name: kxifIndex
kxifIndex.description: The port number, beginning with 1 for the first port.

kxifRxCnt.name: kxifRxCnt
kxifRxCnt.description: The number of small data buffers for receiving packets.

kxifTxCnt.name: kxifTxCnt
kxifTxCnt.description: The maximum size of the port's transmit queue, i.e., the number of packets that can be in the port's transmit queue, waiting to be transmitted.

kxifThreshold.name: kxifThreshold
kxifThreshold.description: Maximum number of combined receive and transmit packet hardware errors before an alarm should be generated.

kxifThresholdTime.name: kxifThresholdTime
kxifThresholdTime.description: The time period (in seconds) to which kxifThreshold applies. A value of zero will disable the kxifThreshold alarm.

kxifRxQueueThresh.name: kxifRxQueueThresh
kxifRxQueueThresh.description: Maximum number of receive packet queue overflow errors before an alarm should be generated.

kxifRxQueueThreshTime.name: kxifRxQueueThreshTime
kxifRxQueueThreshTime.description: The time period (in seconds) to which kxifRxQueueThresh applies. A value of zero will disable the kxifRxQueueThresh alarm.

kxifFunction.name: kxifFunction
kxifFunction.description: The current functional state (protocols which have been activated and are operational) of the port. The following values or combinations are supported: 0x0001 NMS, 0x0002 TBRIDGE, 0x0020 UNIT_NO_BPDU 0x0040 UNIT_RIP, 0x0800 UNIT_ARP,0x1000 UNIT_DUPLEX_HALF 0x2000 UNIT_DUPLEX_AUTO, 0x8000 UNIT_AUTO 0x10000 UNIT_TRUNKING , 0x40000 UNIT_SPEED_10 These values can be configured through the protoTable.

kxifStatisticsTime.name: kxifStatisticsTime
kxifStatisticsTime.description: Length of time during which statistics were collected.

kxuartTable.name: kxuartTable
kxuartTable.description: A list of interface entries; one per UART port.

kxuartEntry.name: kxuartEntry
kxuartEntry.description: A set of objects for an interface entry.

kxuartIndex.name: kxuartIndex
kxuartIndex.description: The ELS-100's port number of the port.

kxuartBaud.name: kxuartBaud
kxuartBaud.description: This is the desired baud rate. Only 1200 baud through 19,200 baud are supported by the ELS-100.

kxuartAlignmentErrors.name: kxuartAlignmentErrors
kxuartAlignmentErrors.description: Number of received packets with frame alignment errors, since the port was last enabled.

kxuartOverrunErrors.name: kxuartOverrunErrors
kxuartOverrunErrors.description: Number of received packets with data overrun errors, since the port was last enabled.

kxprotoTable.name: kxprotoTable
kxprotoTable.description: This table contains configuration information specifying the types of protocols used to bridge and filter frames for each port.

kxprotoEntry.name: kxprotoEntry
kxprotoEntry.description: Each entry in this table specifies which protocols are used by a particular port in the SmartStack.

kxprotoIfIndex.name: kxprotoIfIndex
kxprotoIfIndex.description: Identifies the interface (port) to which this entry's information belongs. The value of this variable corresponds to ifIndex, as well as most of the other port identification values in related MIBs.

kxprotoBridge.name: kxprotoBridge
kxprotoBridge.description: Defines the bridging method to be applied to frames received at, or destined for, this port. Ports may be configured for transparent or none. The UART may only be configured to none.

kxprotoSuppressBpdu.name: kxprotoSuppressBpdu
kxprotoSuppressBpdu.description: Allows transmission of spanning tree protocol packets to be suppressed. If normal(1), 802.1d spanning tree packets are transmitted as usual. If suppressed(2), these packets are not transmitted. This option may be needed for interoperability with non-802.1d spanning tree protocols (e.g., DEC LanBridge 100).

kxprotoRipListen.name: kxprotoRipListen
kxprotoRipListen.description: Specifies whether the port should listen for internet Routing Information Protocol (RFC-1058) packets, in order to build the routing table for the unit.

kxprotoTrunking.name: kxprotoTrunking
kxprotoTrunking.description: Specifies whether SmartStack trunking protocol (an extension to the standard Spanning Tree) is to be used over this port.

kxtrunkTable.name: kxtrunkTable
kxtrunkTable.description: This table describes the trunking status and attributes of the interfaces that are configured for bridge trunking.

kxtrunkEntry.name: kxtrunkEntry
kxtrunkEntry.description: An entry exists in this table for each physical interface (port) that is configured for trunking.

kxtrunkIfIndex.name: kxtrunkIfIndex
kxtrunkIfIndex.description: Identifies a physical interface (port) which is configured for LAN trunking. The value of this variable corresponds to ifIndex, as well as most of the other port identification values in related MIBs.

kxtrunkState.name: kxtrunkState
kxtrunkState.description: If off(1) then this link has not been enabled for trunking. If closed(2) then this link has not yet received any Trunking PDUs. If oneway(3) then incoming Trunking PDUs do not indicate that our PDUs are being successfully received by the far end. If joined(4) then this link is actively participating in the trunk group. If perturbed(5) then this link is actively participating in the trunk group; however, the transmission of data packets has been temporarily stopped due to a change in membership of the group. If helddown(6) then an error has been detected and the link is being held out-of-service until the error clears. If broken(7) then this link has been configured for trunking, but the port is physically non-operational.

kxtrunkRemoteBridgeAddr.name: kxtrunkRemoteBridgeAddr
kxtrunkRemoteBridgeAddr.description: The MAC address portion of the bridge ID of the remote bridge.

kxtrunkRemoteIp.name: kxtrunkRemoteIp
kxtrunkRemoteIp.description: The IP address of the remote bridge, as reported by that bridge for administrative purposes.

kxtrunkLastError.name: kxtrunkLastError
kxtrunkLastError.description: The last reason for failure when the link is in closed, oneway, or helddown state.

kxtrunkLinkOrdinal.name: kxtrunkLinkOrdinal
kxtrunkLinkOrdinal.description: The position of this link within the trunk group.

kxtrunkLinkCount.name: kxtrunkLinkCount
kxtrunkLinkCount.description: The number of links within the trunk group.

kxtrunkLastChange.name: kxtrunkLastChange
kxtrunkLastChange.description: The number of seconds since kxtrunkState changed.

kxWorkGroupNextNumber.name: kxWorkGroupNextNumber
kxWorkGroupNextNumber.description: The next available workgroup number to be used. When creating a new workgroup, it is recommended to read the value of the variable and use it to key into the workgroup table.

kxWorkGroupCurrentCount.name: kxWorkGroupCurrentCount
kxWorkGroupCurrentCount.description: The total number of workgroups currently defined.

kxWorkGroupMaxCount.name: kxWorkGroupMaxCount
kxWorkGroupMaxCount.description: The maximum number of workgroups allowed.

kxWorkGroupTable.name: kxWorkGroupTable
kxWorkGroupTable.description: This table contains work group definitions for the interfaces.

kxWorkGroupEntry.name: kxWorkGroupEntry
kxWorkGroupEntry.description: Each entry in this table contains a definition of a work group.

kxWorkGroupNumber.name: kxWorkGroupNumber
kxWorkGroupNumber.description: An integer that identifies the work group, used as an index to this table.

kxWorkGroupPorts.name: kxWorkGroupPorts
kxWorkGroupPorts.description: A list of all ports within the group. The first octet specified ports 1-8, the second 9-16, etc.

kxWorkGroupType.name: kxWorkGroupType
kxWorkGroupType.description: The type of work group: all - no additional information needs to be supplied.

kxtrapControlTable.name: kxtrapControlTable
kxtrapControlTable.description: This table contains information about the severity of each trap and whether the trap is currently enabled.

kxtrapEnabled.name: kxtrapEnabled
kxtrapEnabled.description: Enable or disable the generation of this trap.

kxtrapSeverity.name: kxtrapSeverity
kxtrapSeverity.description: A user-definable severity, indicating the importance of the trap.

kxtrapSeverityControlTable.name: kxtrapSeverityControlTable
kxtrapSeverityControlTable.description: This table contains information about whether a class of traps of a particular severity is enabled or disabled.

kxtrapSeverityControlSeverity.name: kxtrapSeverityControlSeverity
kxtrapSeverityControlSeverity.description: A user-definable severity, indicating the importance of the trap.

kxtrapSeverityEnable.name: kxtrapSeverityEnable
kxtrapSeverityEnable.description: Enable or disable all traps of a given severity level.

kxtrapIncludeText.name: kxtrapIncludeText
kxtrapIncludeText.description: Whether or not a formatted text string is included in the trap PDU.

kxtrapTime.name: kxtrapTime
kxtrapTime.description: The time, in centiseconds, which should expire between the sending of traps.

kxtrapRetry.name: kxtrapRetry
kxtrapRetry.description: The number of times any enterprise-specific trap is to be sent for a given event. PDUs are retried using a truncated exponential backoff: 2 seconds, 4 seconds, 8 seconds, 16 seconds, and then 32 seconds for all succeeding intervals.

kxtrapNumber.name: kxtrapNumber
kxtrapNumber.description: The number of traps that are in the kxtrapTable.

kxtrapTable.name: kxtrapTable
kxtrapTable.description: This table contains the latest traps that have been generated.

kxtrapEntryIndex.name: kxtrapEntryIndex
kxtrapEntryIndex.description: A number representing the order in which the trap occurred in time. This 32 bit number can wrap.

kxtrapEntryTimeStamp.name: kxtrapEntryTimeStamp
kxtrapEntryTimeStamp.description: The time at which the trap occurred.

kxtrapEntryNumber.name: kxtrapEntryNumber
kxtrapEntryNumber.description: The specific trap number, as specified in the TRAP PDU.

kxtrapEntrySeverity.name: kxtrapEntrySeverity
kxtrapEntrySeverity.description: A user-definable severity, indicating the importance of the trap.

kxmirrorMode.name: kxmirrorMode
kxmirrorMode.description: To turn off port mirroring, or turn on by specifying rx, tx, or (rxandtx) which is the type of data to be mirrored.

kxmirrorDiagPort.name: kxmirrorDiagPort
kxmirrorDiagPort.description: This entry identifies the diagnostic port to which mirrored packet will be destined.

kxmirrorTargetPortLists.name: kxmirrorTargetPortLists
kxmirrorTargetPortLists.description: An octet string specifies the list of ports to be mirrored. The first octet specifies ports 1-8 and the second 9-16.

kxPortFunctionsTrap.name: kxPortFunctionsTrap
kxPortFunctionsTrap.description: Sent whenever the current functional state (active protocols) of the port has changed.

kxRxQueuesTrap.name: kxRxQueuesTrap
kxRxQueuesTrap.description: Sent whenever the number of times that the port's receiver has stopped receiving packets due to buffer space shortages has exceeded the port's limit.

kxTxStormFlagTrap.name: kxTxStormFlagTrap
kxTxStormFlagTrap.description: Sent whenever multicast storm protection has been invoked for the port.

kxTxCongestsTrap.name: kxTxCongestsTrap
kxTxCongestsTrap.description: Sent whenever packets destined for the unit itself were discarded due to lack of buffer space.

kxTrunkStateTrap.name: kxTrunkStateTrap
kxTrunkStateTrap.description: A trunking state change transition has occurred. The possible transitions are: Closed-Oneway Oneway-Perturbed Perturbed-Joined Joined-Helddown Closed-Helddown Oneway-Helddown Perturbed-Helddown

kxTrunkBridgeAddrTrap.name: kxTrunkBridgeAddrTrap
kxTrunkBridgeAddrTrap.description: The associated trunking MAC address of the bridge ID of the remote bridge has changed.

kxTrunkIPAddrTrap.name: kxTrunkIPAddrTrap
kxTrunkIPAddrTrap.description: The associated trunking IP address of the remote bridge has changed.

kxTrunkErrorTrap.name: kxTrunkErrorTrap
kxTrunkErrorTrap.description: An error has occurred in trunking.

kxTrunkLinkOrdinalTrap.name: kxTrunkLinkOrdinalTrap
kxTrunkLinkOrdinalTrap.description: The port's index in the trunking group has changed.

kxTrunkLinkCountTrap.name: kxTrunkLinkCountTrap
kxTrunkLinkCountTrap.description: The number of ports in the trunking group has changed.

kxDiagUnitBootedTrap.name: kxDiagUnitBootedTrap
kxDiagUnitBootedTrap.description: The unit has booted. kxadminFatalErr contains information about why the unit rebooted.

kxStorageFailureTrap.name: kxStorageFailureTrap
kxStorageFailureTrap.description: Sent if the unit's Configuration EEPROM has failed. The unit will not be able to reboot, and must be returned to the factory.

kxIfErrorsTrap.name: kxIfErrorsTrap
kxIfErrorsTrap.description: Sent whenever the number of hardware errors in received and transmitted packets has exceeded the port's limit.
